result.execSummary:
The defendant Ian S. Lund-Paprocki was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Poss.  Defendant plead no contest to count 1.  Count 2 dismissed but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Defendant understood.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis.  Court found that the defendant entered his plea, and waived his constitutional rights freely, voluntarily and intelligently.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of count 1.  Joint recommendation 1 year probation.    The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.    Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, the bar areas of restaurants. Defendant may not possess or consume any alcohol, nor be anywhere alcohol is available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  AODA.  Attorney Poss requested 30 days jail instead of probation, or a combination of fine and jail.  Defendant elected not to exercise his right to allocution.  Court ordered 15 days jail.  Start on or before July 28, 2015 at 6 pm.  20 hours CS.  Set up CS with the coordinator before 7/28.  Complete by 8/31/15.  CC.  $50/mo starting 8/1/15.  FTP  = 1 day jail for every 25 due.
